  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Unstructured citations</strong> are mentions of a business's name, address, and phone number (NAP) in editorial or conversational content — such as a local newspaper article, a blog post recommending businesses in the area, or a community forum thread. Unlike structured citations in formal directories, unstructured citations appear organically in prose and are a strong local SEO signal because they indicate genuine community recognition of the business.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Editorial Citations, Informal Citations</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">8 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Local SEO is built on trust signals. Google uses two main types of citation to verify that a business is real, active, and embedded in its community: structured citations (directory listings) and unstructured citations (editorial mentions). Most businesses focus exclusively on structured citations and miss the significant local ranking leverage available from building unstructured ones.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are unstructured citations?</h2>
        <p>Citations, in the context of local SEO, are any online mention of a business's NAP data — Name, Address, Phone number. The "structured" vs "unstructured" distinction refers to the format:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Structured citations</strong> appear in formal business directories (Google Business Profile, Yelp, Bing Places, TripAdvisor). The information is entered into pre-defined fields and displayed in a consistent format.</li>
          <li><strong>Unstructured citations</strong> appear in editorial content — a local news article, a blog post, a community forum, a social media caption, a podcast description — wherever a business's NAP data appears naturally in text.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Examples of unstructured citations in practice:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>A food blogger writes: "My favourite Friday lunch spot is Maplewood Kitchen at 42 High Street, Jaipur — their thali is unbeatable. Call them at 0141-456-7890 before you go."</li>
          <li>A local newspaper article: "Among the small businesses supporting this year's Diwali market is Sharma Electricals (Shop 12, Sindhi Camp, Jaipur), which has donated lighting for the event."</li>
          <li>A Reddit thread: "Honestly, just call Delhi Plumbing Co. at 011-2345-6789. They're in Karol Bagh and actually show up on time."</li>
        </ul>
        <p>None of these are directory listings, but all of them tell Google something important: real people and publications recognise this business exists at this address and contact number.</p>

        <h2 id="structured-vs-unstructured">Structured vs. unstructured citations — key differences</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Structured Citations</th><th>Unstructured Citations</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Format</strong></td>
                <td>Fixed fields (Name, Address, Phone, URL)</td>
                <td>Prose — NAP mentioned naturally in text</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Location</strong></td><td>Business directories, data aggregators</td><td>News, blogs, forums, social media</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>How to build</strong></td><td>Submit directly to the directory</td><td>Earn through digital PR and community engagement</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Trust signal</strong></td><td>Confirms business details exist in databases</td><td>Confirms organic community awareness</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Scalability</strong></td><td>High — many directories to submit to</td><td>Lower — requires genuine relationship-building</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why Google values unstructured citations</div>
          <p>Structured directory listings can be faked — a business can submit to hundreds of directories without a single real customer knowing the business exists. Unstructured citations are harder to manufacture at scale because they require a real person or publication to write about your business in an authentic context. Google weighs this editorial endorsement accordingly.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why unstructured citations matter for local rankings</h2>
        <p>Google's local search algorithm uses three main categories of signals: Relevance, Distance, and Prominence. Citations feed directly into the Prominence signal.</p>
        <p>Prominence measures how well-known a business is — both online and offline. A business that appears in local newspapers, city guides, community forums, and local blogs is sending a strong prominence signal. Unstructured citations from authoritative local sources (the city's main newspaper, a popular local food blog, a neighbourhood association website) are particularly valuable because they come from sources Google already trusts in a local context.</p>
        <p>BrightLocal's annual local ranking factors survey consistently places citation signals — including unstructured ones — in the top 5 factors for local pack rankings. Businesses in competitive local markets with a strong unstructured citation profile regularly outrank those that rely only on structured directories.</p>

        <h2 id="how-to-build">How to build unstructured citations</h2>
        <p>Unlike structured citations, which you can build by submitting to directories, unstructured citations must be earned. Here are the most effective strategies:</p>

        <h3>1. Local digital PR</h3>
        <p>Reach out to local journalists, news sites, and city lifestyle blogs with stories worth covering. New business openings, community initiatives, charity partnerships, notable achievements, and expert commentary all make valid story pitches. When they cover your story, your business name and address appear in the article — an unstructured citation on an authoritative local domain.</p>

        <h3>2. Sponsor local events and organisations</h3>
        <p>Event organisers, community groups, schools, and sports teams routinely publish sponsor lists on their websites. These mentions include your business name and often your address and phone — exactly the NAP data that constitutes an unstructured citation.</p>

        <h3>3. Guest posts on local and niche blogs</h3>
        <p>Write educational content for local business blogs, industry publications, and community news sites. Your author bio and any natural references to your business within the content create unstructured citations.</p>

        <h3>4. Be active in community forums</h3>
        <p>Neighbourhood Facebook groups, Reddit city subreddits, and Nextdoor are fertile ground for unstructured citations. Engage genuinely — answer questions, share local knowledge, be a visible community member. When others recommend your business in these spaces, or when you include your contact details in a helpful reply, those are unstructured citations.</p>

        <h3>5. Get quoted as a local expert</h3>
        <p>Services like HARO (Help a Reporter Out) and Qwoted connect journalists with expert sources. Responding to local journalist queries positions you as a subject-matter expert and typically results in your business being named and addressed in the published piece.</p>

        <h2 id="nap-consistency">NAP consistency in unstructured citations</h2>
        <p>The same NAP consistency rules that apply to structured citations apply here. If your business name on your GBP is "Sharma Electricals Ltd." but a blog post mentions "Sharma Electrical Services," Google may not correctly associate the two.</p>
        <p>Where you have influence over the published content — a guest post, a press release, a sponsorship listing — use your exact legal business name, your exact address format (including suite number if applicable), and your exact primary phone number.</p>
        <p>Where you do not have control — a journalist's article, a community forum post — monitor for inaccuracies and politely request corrections if the NAP is significantly wrong. A minor abbreviation ("St" instead of "Street") is acceptable; a wrong phone number or address needs correction.</p>

        <h2 id="find-existing">Finding your existing unstructured citations</h2>
        <p>Before building new unstructured citations, audit what you already have. Use these methods:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Google search:</strong> Search for "Your Business Name" -site:yourdomain.com and scan for editorial mentions.</li>
          <li><strong>Semrush Brand Monitoring:</strong> Tracks mentions across news, blogs, and social media, with filters for sources that do not include a link.</li>
          <li><strong>Google Alerts:</strong> Set up ongoing alerts for your business name to catch new unstructured citations as they appear.</li>
          <li><strong>Ahrefs Content Explorer:</strong> Search for your business name in editorial content and identify which pages mention you but do not link to you.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common mistakes with unstructured citations</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ignoring them entirely:</strong> Many local SEO campaigns focus exclusively on structured directory submissions and leave significant local ranking opportunity on the table.</li>
          <li><strong>Inconsistent NAP:</strong> Not monitoring how your business name and address appear in editorial content can result in a fragmented citation profile that confuses Google's entity matching.</li>
          <li><strong>Targeting irrelevant publications:</strong> An unstructured citation on a high-DA site that has nothing to do with your local market or industry carries less weight than a mention in a local community site with lower authority but high local relevance.</li>
          <li><strong>Not tracking citations over time:</strong> Editorial content can be updated or deleted. A citation that existed yesterday may not exist tomorrow. Quarterly audits using the methods above help you monitor your unstructured citation footprint.</li>
        </ul>

