            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>An unstructured citation is any mention of your business name, address, or phone number that appears in editorial content — a blog post, news article, review, or forum thread — rather than in a structured business directory. Google uses these mentions to verify that a business exists and is embedded in its local community.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between structured and unstructured citations?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Structured citations appear in formal directories (Yelp, Google Business Profile, Yellow Pages) in a consistent NAP format. Unstructured citations appear in editorial content without a fixed format — a newspaper might mention your business name and street address in an article about local events. Both signal legitimacy to Google, but through different channels.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Do unstructured citations still matter for local rankings?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Studies by Whitespark and BrightLocal consistently show citations as a top local ranking factor. Unstructured citations carry additional weight because they suggest organic community awareness — a local newspaper or blogger mentioning your business without being paid to list it is a stronger trust signal than a paid directory entry.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How do you build unstructured citations?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Unstructured citations are earned through community involvement, digital PR, guest posting on local blogs, sponsoring events, being quoted in local news, and generating word-of-mouth online. You cannot simply submit your information the way you do with structured citations — they require genuine local engagement or outreach to journalists and bloggers.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does NAP consistency matter for unstructured citations?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Even in editorial content, your business name and address should be consistent with your Google Business Profile. If a news article uses an abbreviation of your street address or a variation of your brand name, Google may struggle to associate the mention with your GBP listing. Always request consistent formatting when you can.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

